He Said, She
Said
------------

Would Baldoni win his case against The New York Times? I=E2=80=99d
say it=E2=80=99s about as likely as an Oscar nod=E2=80=94long odds, indeed.=
 What, exactly, is the filmmaker-actor accusing the Times of getting wrong?=
 It=E2=80=99s murky. Yes, he=E2=80=99s ticked off that Megan Twohey, who fa=
mously exposed Harvey Weinstein=E2=80=99s history of sexual crimes while re=
porting alongside Jodi Kantor, presented a lopsided narrative of his allege=
d misdeeds. But let=E2=80=99s be clear: Bias isn=E2=80=99t illegal. Only de=
monstrable falsehoods can
qualify as defamation, and complaints about vague character attacks don=E2=
=80=99t usually hold up in court, particularly in California, where anti-SL=
APP laws encourage judges to quickly toss cases that interfere with free sp=
eech.

=C2=A0

The bulk of Baldoni=E2=80=99s 87-page complaint appears aimed more at the c=
ourt of public opinion than the judiciary, emphasizing his side of the he-s=
aid, she-said beef. Take Lively=E2=80=99s accusation
of Baldoni=E2=80=99s unwanted kissing and discussion of his sex life: He co=
unters that she refused to meet with the production=E2=80=99s intimacy coor=
dinator, and that the creative process involved collaboratively designing s=
cenes, which he found appropriate. This alternate narrative, however, is ju=
st that=E2=80=94an alternate narrative. In other words, a different interpr=
etation of the same facts.

=C2=A0

You have to look past long
digressions, which have nothing to do with what the Times reported, to disc=
ern what Baldoni alleges that the paper factually misstated. Baldoni, for i=
nstance, says he did not agree to a 30-point list of Lively=E2=80=99s deman=
ds after she raised concerns about his behavior, stating he was never even =
presented with such a document. Yet the Times never mentioned such a list; =
rather, it noted that Baldoni=E2=80=99s company, Wayfarer, had agreed to te=
rms to ensure a safe work
environment.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Even if the Times made an error, or insinuated that Baldoni was guilty of s=
exual harassment, how much responsibility does the paper bear in conveying =
Lively=E2=80=99s account? This question introduces some legal nuances. Whil=
e publications can be liable even when quoting others, repetition of someon=
e=E2=80=99s complaint to a government body like a court or administration a=
gency typically
receives protection under the =E2=80=9Cfair report privilege.=E2=80=9D This=
 legal shield is vital, allowing journalists extra latitude to cover issues=
 in the public interest, such as how the government functions and how it ha=
ndles disputes that require government intervention. There=E2=80=99s even a=
 vetting process=E2=80=94lawyers confirm the veracity of what they submit i=
n court, under the penalty of sanctions or even the loss of their licenses =
to practice law. Journalists, such as myself, often rely on their diligence=
=2E

=C2=A0

Still, when I first saw the Times story, I wasn=E2=80=99t clear whether thi=
s privilege would apply. Was Lively=E2=80=99s complaint actually filed with=
 the California Civil Rights Department? Did anyone check=E2=80=94or was th=
e story based on some embargoed copy and rushed once TMZ published its own =
version? And did Twohey and the other reporters expand their investigation =
beyond the complaint? The Times claimed its
story was grounded in a thorough review of =E2=80=9Cthousands of pages of o=
riginal documents.=E2=80=9D Was that puffery?=C2=A0

=C2=A0

I=E2=80=99ve spent the last few days digging into the editorial process and=
 speaking with insiders off the record, and I=E2=80=99m still not absolutel=
y certain privilege will apply. Fortunately for the Times, there are probab=
ly other defenses at play, but it also wouldn=E2=80=99t be a surprise if th=
ings get messy before
this saga is resolved.=C2=A0

California Dreamin=E2=80=99
---------------------

One mystery in particular has captivated the legal community
regarding Baldoni=E2=80=99s lawsuit: Why opt for a California state court? =
After all, not only is there an expansive state anti-SLAPP law that swiftly=
 dismisses meritless cases, it also awards legal costs=E2=80=94meaning Bald=
oni could be forced to pay the Times=E2=80=99s legal fees. Plus, the Times =
can kick this to federal court and pursue an immediate appeal if its anti-S=
LAPP bid fails. In other words, don=E2=80=99t expect a trial anytime soon.

=C2=A0

When I contacted Freedman, he was uncharacteristically tight-lipped about h=
is strategy. My guess? He=E2=80=99s more comfortable with the local legal a=
rena, betting on the known quantities on the bench.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

However, I do wonder if it has anything to do with a notable ruling last ye=
ar in former film financier Ryan Kavanaugh=E2=80=99s case against podcaster=
 Ethan
Klein, where a judge allowed a libel suit to proceed despite an anti-SLAPP =
challenge centered on the application of fair report privilege. The dispute=
 is terribly complicated=E2=80=94see my prior report ( https://puck.news/ry=
an-kavanaughs-media-legal-thriller/?utm_campaign=3DWhat+I%27m+Hearing%2B+-+=
SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F7%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWhat+I%27m+Hearing%2B+-+SUBSCRIB=
ERS+%281%2F7%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm=
_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) for details=E2=80=94but long story short: Klei=
n failed in his attempt to invoke the shield because the judge didn=E2=80=
=99t think what he repeated about Kavanaugh operating a =E2=80=9CPonzi sche=
me=E2=80=9D was
particularly fair. (Incidentally, California=E2=80=99s 2nd appellate divisi=
on will hold a hearing on this matter on Wednesday, delving into republicat=
ion liability and the almost metaphysical nature of what constitutes a =E2=
=80=9Cfiling=E2=80=9D for privilege purposes.)

