=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Like many in Hollywood, my New Year=E2=80=
=99s Eve sparkled with
fireworks, champagne, and a dash of the <strong>Blake Lively</strong>-<stro=
ng>Justin Baldoni</strong> melodrama. Hours before the ball dropped in Time=
s Square, Baldoni slapped <em>The</em> <em>New York Times</em> with a $250 =
million defamation lawsuit, accusing the paper of betraying its journalisti=
c mission by coordinating with Lively=E2=80=99s team to publish a sensation=
alized account of whatever transpired during and after the shooting of <em>=
It Ends With Us. </em><strong>Bryan Freedman</strong>,
Baldoni=E2=80=99s attorney, lambasted the <em>Times</em> for basing much of=
 its story on an =E2=80=9Cunverified and self-serving=E2=80=9D complaint th=
at Lively had submitted to the California Civil Rights Department. The fili=
ng, Freedman said, should have remained =E2=80=9Cconfidential unless leaked=
=E2=80=94as it was here.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bott=
om:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Freedman added =
that while a filing with a civil rights department can precede a lawsuit (i=
ndeed, Lively has now sued
in New York), =E2=80=9Cit is clear that litigation was never her ultimate g=
oal. Her real intention was to weaponize the appearance of legitimacy.=E2=
=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">I had to chuckle. This was <em>Bryan Freedman</e=
m>, a guy who=E2=80=99s well-known for his skill and flair at working the p=
ress outside the hushed quiet of arbitration when it suits his clients. Doi=
ng press around an administrative complaint is practically a Freedman trade=
mark.
And I=E2=80=99m <em>not </em>knocking him. Freedman is a pioneer of sorts.<=
/p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;=
">Still, in this dispute, Freedman proceeded in a way I found, frankly, sur=
prising: In the complaint, he included correspondence from journalists cove=
ring the Lively-Baldoni story. These reporters had shared with Baldoni publ=
icist <strong>Melissa Nathan</strong>=E2=80=94and later, directly with Free=
dman=E2=80=94their hearsay, opinions on peers=E2=80=99 coverage, and snippe=
ts of
gossip rarely seen in court documents. Most striking was the correspondence=
 from the <em>Daily Mail</em>=E2=80=99s <strong>James Vituscka</strong>, wh=
o badmouthed Lively=E2=80=99s publicist, <strong>Leslie Sloane</strong>, in=
 private texts, and then sent Freedman a screenshot of their conversation, =
accompanied by the message: =E2=80=9CI hope this helps in some way.=E2=80=
=9D Blowing up your sources by using texts from journalists as legal fodder=
 is a good way to make sure journalists stop taking your calls.=C2=A0</p></=
