ng wrong? It=E2=80=99s murky. Yes, he=E2=80=99s ticked off that <strong>Meg=
an Twohey</strong>, who famously exposed <strong>Harvey Weinstein</strong>=
=E2=80=99s history of sexual crimes while reporting alongside <strong>Jodi =
Kantor</strong>, presented a lopsided narrative of his alleged misdeeds. Bu=
t let=E2=80=99s be clear: Bias isn=E2=80=99t illegal. Only demonstrable fal=
sehoods can
qualify as defamation, and complaints about vague character attacks don=E2=
=80=99t usually hold up in court, particularly in California, where anti-SL=
APP laws encourage judges to quickly toss cases that interfere with free sp=
eech.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"mar=
gin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">The bulk of Baldoni=E2=80=99s 87-page complaint a=
ppears aimed more at the court of public opinion than the judiciary, emphas=
izing his side of the he-said, she-said beef. Take Lively=E2=80=99s accusat=
ion
of Baldoni=E2=80=99s unwanted kissing and discussion of his sex life: He co=
unters that she refused to meet with the production=E2=80=99s intimacy coor=
dinator, and that the creative process involved collaboratively designing s=
cenes, which he found appropriate. This alternate narrative, however, is ju=
st that=E2=80=94an alternate narrative. In other words, a different interpr=
etation of the same facts.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">You have to look past long
digressions, which have nothing to do with what the <em>Times</em> reported=
, to discern what Baldoni alleges that the paper <em>factually</em> misstat=
ed. Baldoni, for instance, says he did <em>not</em> agree to a 30-point lis=
t of Lively=E2=80=99s demands after she raised concerns about his behavior,=
 stating he was never even presented with such a document. Yet the <em>Time=
s</em> never mentioned such a list; rather, it noted that Baldoni=E2=80=99s=
 company, Wayfarer, had agreed to terms to ensure a safe work
environment.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p=
 style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Even if the <em>Times</em> made an e=
rror, or insinuated that Baldoni was guilty of sexual harassment, how much =
responsibility does the paper bear in conveying Lively=E2=80=99s account? T=
his question introduces some legal nuances. While publications can be liabl=
e even when quoting others, repetition of someone=E2=80=99s complaint to a =
government body like a court or administration agency typically
receives protection under the =E2=80=9Cfair report privilege.=E2=80=9D This=
 legal shield is vital, allowing journalists extra latitude to cover issues=
 in the public interest, such as how the government functions and how it ha=
ndles disputes that require government intervention. There=E2=80=99s even a=
 vetting process=E2=80=94lawyers confirm the veracity of what they submit i=
n court, under the penalty of sanctions or even the loss of their licenses =
to practice law. Journalists, such as myself, often rely on their diligence=
=2E</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bo=
ttom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:=
0;margin-bottom:0px;">Still, when I first saw the<em> Times</em> story, I w=
asn=E2=80=99t clear whether this privilege would apply. Was Lively=E2=80=99=
s complaint actually filed with the California Civil Rights Department? Did=
 anyone check=E2=80=94or was the story based on some embargoed copy and rus=
hed once TMZ published its own version? And did Twohey and the other report=
ers expand their investigation beyond the complaint? The <em>Times</em> cla=
imed its
story was grounded in a thorough review of =E2=80=9C<em>thousands</em> of p=
ages of original documents.=E2=80=9D Was that puffery?=C2=A0</p><p style=3D=
"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">I=E2=80=99ve=
 spent the last few days digging into the editorial process and speaking wi=
th insiders off the record, and I=E2=80=99m still not absolutely certain pr=
ivilege will apply. Fortunately for the <em>Times</em>, there are probably =
other defenses at play, but it also wouldn=E2=80=99t be a surprise if thing=
s get messy before
this saga is resolved.=C2=A0</p></div>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
